   "source": [
    "#Q4. What is the significance of the spectral theorem in the context of the Eigen-Decomposition approach?\n",
    "#How is it related to the diagonalizability of a matrix? Explain with an example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68839855-c116-4ae6-aaa9-8df12703bdb8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The spectral theorem states that a matrix A is diagonalizable if and only if A has n linearly independent eigenvectors. \n",
    "\n",
    "The theorem also states that if A is a real symmetric matrix, then it can be diagonalized by an orthogonal matrix. \n",
    "\n",
    "The significance of the spectral theorem in the context of the Eigen-Decomposition approach is that it provides a way to decompose a matrix into its eigenvalues and eigenvectors. This decomposition can be used to simplify calculations involving matrices, such as computing powers of matrices"
   ]
  },
