    "#Q7. Can you explain the geometric interpretation of eigenvectors and eigenvalues?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "59cca63a-1ec9-410f-8156-a09e09c124e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The geometric interpretation of eigenvectors and eigenvalues can be seen in the context of linear transformations . An eigenvector of a matrix A represents a direction that is not changed by the linear transformation represented by A , but is only scaled by a factor λ known as the eigenvalue . In other words, when A is applied to an eigenvector v , the result is a scalar multiple λv of v .\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
